{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-03","name":"Hugh Hulse","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Hugh Hulse","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Hugh"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Hulse"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"Hugh de Holes","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1342–1407","fullLifespan":"1342–1407","portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/rra7j/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"memoryArtifacts":[{"memoryType":"DOCUMENT","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7720-111030-91-88/dist.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/134282440","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7720-111030-91-88/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-7720-111030-91-88/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","headline":"1882. Hulse Family - The History of the County Palatine, Vol 3, Page 464","description":"Page 464, Vol III, 1882.\nThe History of the County Palatine and City of Chester; Compiled from Original Evidences in Public Offices, The Harleian and Cottonian MSS. , Parochial Registers, Private Muniments, Unpublished MS. Collections of Successive Cheshire Antiquaries, and A personal survey of every township in the county ; Incorporated with a republication of King's Vale Royal, And Leycester's Cheshire Antiquities.\nBy George Ormerod, Esq. , LL.D. F.R.S. & F.S.A.  \nIn 3 Volumes, Volume III,\nFirst Edition, 1819 - 472 pages, Second Edition, 1882 \nRevised and Enlarged 1882 - 879 Pages\nBy Thomas Helsby, Esq. , of Lincoln's Inn, Barrister-at-Law.","@type":"ImageObject"},{"memoryType":"PHOTO","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7768-123700-40908-84/dist.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/164615592","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7768-123700-40908-84/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-7768-123700-40908-84/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","@type":"ImageObject"}],"birthDate":"+1342","birthPlace":{"address":"Northwich, Cheshire, England","geo":{"latitude":53.2608,"longitude":-2.5118,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1407","deathPlace":{"address":"Cheshire, England","geo":{"latitude":53.18268,"longitude":-2.53046,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\nHugh de Holes was the second son of Sir William de Huls, Knt, and his wife.\n\nHugh's mother was either the unnamed daughter and heir of David de Norbury, son of Roger, third son of William de Bulkylegh, lord of Norbury ex dono patris [by the gift of his father], or Hugh's mother was Sibill, daughter of William son of Hugh de Norbury.\n\nHugh married Ellen Bruen of Picmere in 36 Edward III.\n\n«b»Hugh and Ellen had children:«/b»\n1.) Sir Hugh de Hulse of Raby, Cheshire, kt, chief justice of Chester 19 Richard II at 40 marks per annum, a judge of the King's Bench 12 and 20 Richard II, died in 3 Henry V, when an inquisition was taken, married Margaret or Margery, daughter and heir of John Domville of Oxton and Brunstath, who was living in 21 Ricahrd II and 5 Henry IV;\n\n2.) Roger de Holes, heir in remainder in tail of Elston, 19 Richard II;\n\nHugh was granted lands in Little Neston in 7 Richard II.","sourceList":[{"title":"Hugh Hulse in Our Royal, Titled, Noble, and Commoner Ancestors","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://our-royal-titled-noble-and-commoner-ancestors.com/p812.htm#i24384","sourceUri":"312M-Q9R"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"1","year":"1342","date":"1342","place":"Northwich, Cheshire, England"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1342","date":"134